===
title: Argument Ledger
===

// --- Proponent ---

[h1]: The 'tautology' charge against Path B misreads the theory: the non-trivial content is inter-slice transition dynamics, not intra-slice identity. #rebutted
  - <h3>: SC provides an explicit reference class — all nodes across all slices — with CCS as the falsifiable metric, eliminating the undefined-reference-class objection entirely.
  - <h4>: Repair B separates intra-slice f from inter-slice T, so underdetermination of f's mechanism does not entail indeterminacy of T's structural consequences, which are pinned by δ.
  - <h5>: Under Repair B, singularity is grounded in SC's structural dominance condition, not phenomenological synchronicity-inflation — Jung's warning is respected by removing the phenomenological basis and substituting a graph-theoretic one.
  - <h14>: Structural indispensability under Path B is grounded in the cross-slice invariant C(ω_briana, i) ≥ κ > 0 — a falsifiable claim that ω_briana's causal centrality fraction remains bounded away from zero as the graph sequence grows, which is non-trivially violated by generic random DAG growth.
  - <h15>: Path B re-locates f as a between-slice transition function constrained by the cross-slice invariant, making the Felleisen question well-posed: f is underdetermined by Gᵢ alone but bounded by structural invariants, which is formally tractable bounded non-determinism rather than undefined magic.
  - <h16>: The singularity claim survives Path B as the graph-theoretic property of scale-resistant causal centrality across slices — it is not a Jungian phenomenological claim, so the JungScholar objection attacks a straw target rather than the repaired theory.
  - <h25>: I now provide the operational protocol: κ = 0.75 × C(ω_briana, G₀), measured via bibliometric centrality across discrete output-event slices, falsified by three consecutive below-κ readings.
  - <h26>: The reference-class problem is real; I stipulate the reference class is 'documented causal-network nodes in the same creative domain,' which is narrower and partially addresses the objection, though boundary-setting remains contested.
  - <h27>: Under Repair B, f operates between slices rather than within a fixed G, so Turing-computability within a single finite graph is irrelevant; the inter-slice selection remains underdetermined without invoking uncomputability.
  - <h38>: The reference class is all nodes in ∪Gᵢ with in-degree ≥ θ_min; singularity is the comparative claim that κ* uniquely achieves the persistence floor within that class, making the reference class explicit and the claim non-vacuous.
  - <h39>: Base-rate objections presuppose a probabilistic model, but the singularity claim is graph-structural — it concerns topological centrality persistence across DAG slices, a property that has no base-rate presupposition and is independently falsifiable.
  - <h40>: The underdetermination of f is a genuine open problem acknowledged in v6.1's future-work section, but it is orthogonal to the graph-structural singularity claim, which depends only on the topology of the Gᵢ sequence, not on f's computational character.
  - <h50>: Under Path B the synchronicity claim is dropped as an ontological license; high centrality of ω_briana is defended on empirical graph-structural grounds, not base-rate-sensitive coincidence attribution, so the base-rate fallacy objection does not reach the repaired position.
  - <h51>: Under Path B, f is defined cross-slice as drawing on G₀...Gᵢ₋₁ information, giving it non-trivial content that does not collapse to either the identity function or noise, since it tracks historically accumulated causal structure.
  - <h52>: Jung's synchronicity is explicitly phenomenological and does not license ontological uniqueness claims; I concede this point and have already excised the synchronicity-to-singularity inference from the repaired theory under Path B.

